2.50 pm Runs on the board in a virtual final, and 281 is a pretty decent score but New Zealand were heading north of 300 with Ross Taylor making his 16th ODI century - the most by a batsman from his country. He says: "pleasing to hit a hundred in a must-win game, but we're 15 or 20 short. We got a few good runs late in the innings though. Dean Brownlie played really well on his comeback [hitting 63 off 78], at his home ground. Australia did really well in the back end, bowling back of a length and the cross-seamers and slower balls. Hopefully we can learn from them and defend this."

The combination of Pat Cummins and James Faulkner - bowling into the wicket to extract occasional extra bounce - and then Mitchell Starc generating reverse swing at nearly 150 kph made sure New Zealand had a tough time in the back end of their innings. They lost 5 wickets for 42 runs between the 32nd and 41st over which forced Taylor to reassess. He was batting ever so fluently, established by the fact he was on 4 when Brownlie was 40 and beat his partner to a half-century. Colin Munro, James Neesham and MItchell Santner couldn't rotate strike well enough and Taylor barely got any strike in the final few overs. Santner, at least, made up for it in the end, hitting three boundaries in three balls to push the score up to 281. Australia with their noses in front, but things take wild turns in chases. So stick around. We'll be back in half an hour

Alex: "Fair enough that NZ's middle order looks weak. We have only recently lost the experience of guys like Elliot, Vettori, and Natham McCullum (not to mention his brother Baz up top), and we are missing Guppy too. Give us time to build back. You can't get experience by dropping newcomers."

Mitch: ""you can't get experience by dropping newcomers" Well they dropped Henry Nicholls when One Dayers are his best format, averages over 44 in List A"

Glen: "Alex: interesting that players with 20 (Munro), 27 (Broom) and 30 (Neesham) ODIs under their belts are considered newcomers..." Well, Broom's making his second coming and Neesham's had a bit of a stop-start career so maybe the point stands.
